gov.nasa.ial.mde.solver.symbolic
Class AnalyzedEquation

java.lang.Object
  gov.nasa.ial.mde.solver.symbolic.AnalyzedEquation
All Implemented Interfaces:
AnalyzedItem
public class AnalyzedEquation
extends Object
implements AnalyzedItem

Analyzes an input string to extract features associated with equation(s). Determines variables, coordinate system, and type of equation e.g. Cartesian, Polar or Parametric. Acts as a screener to determine which classifier to apply.

Since:
1.0
Version:
1.0
Author:
Dan Dexter, Dr. Robert Shelton

getEquationType

public int getEquationType()
Returns the type of the equation as a coded integer which can be compared to the constants UNKNOWN, CARTESIAN, POLAR or PARAMETRIC defined in this class.

Returns:
an integer corresponding to UNKNOWN, CARTESIAN, POLAR or PARAMETRIC. Might be useful as a variable in a case statement. The value UNKNOWN corresponds to an equation that did not parse correctly. The alternate isUnknown|Cartesian|Polar|Parametric methods are provided. Currently, parametric equations are not supported.
See Also:
UNKNOWN, CARTESIAN, POLAR, PARAMETRIC

getEquationProperties

public int getEquationProperties()
Returns an integer that codes boolean properties of the equation.

Returns:
an integer code for the various equation properties to check against the enumeration constants CONSTANT|FUNCTION|POLYNOMIAL of this class. Might be useful as a variable in a case statement.
See Also:
GENERIC, CONSTANT, FUNCTION, POLYNOMIAL, QUADRATIC, MORE_THAN_TWO_VARIABLES, UNDEFINED, NO_SOLUTION

isConstant

public boolean isConstant()
Does the input string describe an equation with no reference to an independent variable, does it define a constant.

Returns:
true if the value(s) of the dependent variable do not depend on the independent variable. Does not strictly mean constant, in the sense that the input string "y^3 = y" would evoke a return value of true, even though this relation does not define a function. The meaning of "constant" in this context is that we need only compute the dependent variable once.
See Also:
CONSTANT, getEquationProperties()

isFunction

public boolean isFunction()
Determines syntactically if the input string defines a function. It may return false in situations for which the input string is sufficiently obfuscated that the syntactic tests fail, for example "exp(x^2 - y) = 1" which is algebraically equivalent to y = x^2 -- the code will not discover such an equivalence.

Returns:
true if and only if the equation is guaranteed to define a function, independent of the value of the independent variable. A return value of "false" should suggest testing points over the indicated domain.
See Also:
FUNCTION, getEquationProperties()

getActualVariables

public String[] getActualVariables()
Returns the two variables used in the equation if the equation only contains one variable, makes a reasonable guess as to the other implied variable.

Returns:
two-element string array containing the equation variables.

getDVPCoefficients

public Expression[] getDVPCoefficients()
Returns an array of expressions corresponding to the coefficients of the polynomial for the dependent variable.

Note that this AnalyzedEquation is solvable if and only if each DVP coefficient contains at most one variable, and that variable is identical to the independent variable.

Returns:
an array of expressions c[k], where c[k] is the coefficient of y^k in the polynomial for y.
